  "prompt": "How do deaf people communicate?",
  "response": "Deaf people use a variety of methods to communicate, depending on their preferences, needs, and cultural background. Here are some of the primary ways deaf individuals communicate:\n\n1. **Sign Language**:  \n   - **American Sign Language (ASL)**: A complete, natural language used in the U.S. and parts of Canada, with its own grammar and syntax.  \n   - **Other Sign Languages**: Different countries have their own sign languages, such as British Sign Language (BSL), Auslan (Australia), and many others.  \n   - **International Sign**: A simplified sign language used for international communication.  \n\n2. **Lip Reading (Speech Reading)**:  \n   - Some deaf individuals rely on observing the speaker\u2019s lip movements, facial expressions, and body language to understand spoken language.  \n\n3. **Spoken Language**:  \n   - Some deaf people use spoken language, especially if they grew up using hearing aids, cochlear implants, or other assistive devices.  \n   - They may also use speech therapy to improve their ability to speak and articulate words clearly.\n\n4. **Written Communication**:  \n   - Writing or typing, such as through text messages, emails, or notes, is a common method for communication between deaf and hearing individuals.  \n\n5. **Assistive Technology**:  \n   - **Hearing Aids and Cochlear Implants**: Some deaf individuals use these devices to enhance their ability to hear and process sound.  \n   - **Video Relay Services (VRS)**: Allows deaf individuals to communicate with hearing people via a sign language interpreter over video.  \n   - **Captioned Phones**: Phones that display real-time text captions of spoken conversations.  \n   - **Text-to-Speech Apps**: Software that converts spoken language into text or vice versa.  \n\n6. **Gesture and Body Language**:  \n   - Deaf individuals may use gestures, facial expressions, and body language to convey meaning, especially in informal settings.  \n\n7. **Deaf Culture and Community**:  \n   - Many deaf people are part of a vibrant Deaf community that values sign language and Deaf culture. This community often serves as a cultural and social network, fostering communication through shared experiences and values.  \n\nThe choice of communication method depends on the individual\u2019s level of hearing loss, upbringing, education, and personal preferences. Deaf communication is diverse and adaptable to different contexts and needs.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
